{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472097","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472097"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:55:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"995"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/995"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.15,0.3,0.49,0.05,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54692"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"995","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/995"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"995"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40221"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2105"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6198"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6331"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6389"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16667"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54692"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 10-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a six-hour history of central colicky abdominal pain. He has also had mild but tolerable joint pain over the past two days. His parent explains that he has been unwell with coryzal symptoms for the past few weeks. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is up to date with immunisations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 100/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg (elevated for his age, gender and height), respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. He has a palpable purpuric rash distributed on the buttocks and legs bilaterally. His abdomen is diffusely tender with no localising signs, rigidity or guarding. He has no pitting oedema or swelling of his face.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis shows microscopic haematuria.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Discharge home with GP follow-up","Admit for observation, leg elevation, analgesia and blood pressure monitoring","Commence oral prednisolone","Commence oral amoxicillin","Arrange urgent exploratory laparotomy"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has Henoch-Schonlein purpura (HSP), an IgA-mediated small vessel vasculitis, given his abdominal pain, joint pain, palpable purpuric rash distributed on the buttocks and legs bilaterally, and recent upper respiratory infection. First line treatment in uncomplicated HSP is supportive care, including bed rest, leg elevation, paracetamol and ibuprofen.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient has microscopic haematuria and mildly elevated blood pressure in addition to the classic signs of HSP, it is not appropriate to \u003Cstrong\u003Edischarge him home\u003C/strong\u003E without first monitoring and treating with conservative measures. If he responds well to conservative therapy and his blood pressure normalises, then discharge with GP follow-up may be appropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdmission for observation, leg elevation, analgesia and blood pressure monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This allows for close monitoring of his condition, management of symptoms, and assessment of any potential complications, particularly given the presence of microscopic haematuria and elevated blood pressure.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral prednisolone\u003C/strong\u003E is useful in the treatment of HSP, it is reserved for children with moderate to severe abdominal and joint pain that is refractory to conservative measures. As such, regular paracetamol, short-term NSAIDs, and bed rest should be trialled first. About one-third of patients with HSP will have some evidence of renal impairment and if that is the case, NSAIDs should be avoided.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere are no signs of bacterial infection to indicate \u003Cstrong\u003Eoral amoxicillin\u003C/strong\u003E. The recent coryzal illness was likely viral in origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis patient does not have any signs concerning for surgical abdominal conditions such as appendicitis or peritonism. Therefore, \u003Cstrong\u003Eurgent exploratory laparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Henoch-Schonlein purpura is an IgA-mediated small vessel vasculitis that presents with abdominal pain, joint pain, and palpable purpura on the lower limbs, often on a background of a recent viral illness.","Henoch-Schonlein purpura is treated conservatively with bed rest and analgesia, however, abnormalities in blood pressure or urinalysis warrant admission and monitoring.","It is essential to remember that the abdominal pain can precede, accompany or follow the purpuric rash."],"references":["https://www.rch.org.au/clinicalguide/guideline_index/HenochSchonlein_Purpura/","Roache-Robinson P, Hotwagner DT. Henoch Sch\u00f6nlein Purpura. [Updated 2020 Dec 2]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537252/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40221"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"995"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"40221","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/40221"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-09T13:40:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-09T13:42:01+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"995"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54692"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"696","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/696"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Henoch-sch\u00f6nlein purpura","synonyms":["HSP","Henoch-Schonlein purpura"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2021-05-19T22:40:10+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"2"}},"headin